				<div itemprop="commentText" class='post entry-content '>
					<blockquote class='ipsBlockquote' data-author="&#39;Earthenware&#39;" data-cid="1414425" data-time="1361633122" data-date="23 February 2013 - 10:25 AM"><p>So, realistically, will mysql functions ever be removed from PHP? I reckon not, but it would be interesting to hear the opinions of people better informed than I. Thanks.<br /></p></blockquote><br />Yes, they will.  See <a href='https://wiki.php.net/rfc/mysql_deprecation' class='bbc_url' title='External link' rel='external'>Request for Comments: ext/mysql deprecation</a> for the PHP Dev&#39;s opinions on the matter.<br /><br />Whether ISP&#39;s continue to offer a version of PHP that has them is up to them, they can do what they want.  I would guess most hosts would probably keep the option to run php 5.3/5.4/5.5 w/ t he mysql extension enabled for quite a while.  That&#39;s no excuse to keep using something that has been deprecated though.<br /><br />If you&#39;re having issues with MySQLi then you could try using PDO and see if that works any better for you.  Otherwise try posting your code for someone to review and see if there are any issues.<br />
					
